HEADWORD: Gummite
<hw>Gum"mite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So called because it
occurs in rounded or flattened pieces which look like gum.]</ety>
<fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A yellow amorphous mineral, essentially a
hydrated oxide of uranium derived from the alteration of
uraninite.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gummosity</ent>⟦br⟧
